---
import { getCollection } from "astro:content";
import BaseLayout from "../components/layout/BaseLayout.astro";

const REPO = "https://github.com/coderturtle/closed-book";
const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;

const recentEntries = (await getCollection("buildlog", ({ data }) => !data.draft))
  .sort((a, b) => b.data.pubDate.valueOf() - a.data.pubDate.valueOf())
  .slice(0, 3);
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Closed Book: guide"
  description="Build it with Claude. Prove you don't need Claude to pass."
>
  <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold">Closed Book</h1>
  <p class="mt-2 text-lg opacity-80">
    Build it with Claude. Prove you don't need Claude to pass.
  </p>

  <div class="post-body mt-10">
    <p>
      This page is orientation for anyone landing on the deployed site rather than the repo
      directly. The workshop itself, ten modules building toward Anthropic's real Claude
      Certified Architect exams, lives in the <a href={REPO}>repo</a>, whose own README covers
      the same ground in more detail once you've cloned it.
    </p>

    <h2>Two gates, not one, deliberately in tension</h2>
    <p>
      Every module's core exercise is built hands-on through your own Claude Code session: a
      real agentic loop, a designed MCP tool, a CLAUDE.md hierarchy, whatever that module's
      exam domain actually asks a practitioner to build. Then, before moving on, you{" "}
      <strong>close the session</strong> and take a timed, closed-book practice checkpoint,
      no AI, no notes, because that's the one condition under which Anthropic's real exam
      actually happens. Neither tier substitutes for the other.
    </p>

    <h2>Anchored to Anthropic's own published exam guides, not third-party summaries</h2>
    <p>
      This workshop's module arc is built directly from Anthropic's own <em>Claude Certified
      Architect – Foundations</em> and <em>– Professional</em> exam guide PDFs (fetched and
      read in full, not summarized from secondary sources; an early research pass found several
      third-party "exam prep" sites recycling identical, unreliable domain lists across
      different exam pages). See the repo's <code>docs/workshop-design.md</code> for the full
      research this arc is grounded in.
    </p>

    <h2>What you walk away with</h2>
    <p>
      Two different things get built during each module: your own judgment, and a reusable
      artifact you keep. See each module's own README (once authored) for the evidence behind
      its specific gate.
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong>You</strong> get practiced judgment: recalling why a design choice is correct
        without a tool doing the reasoning for you, which is a rehearsed skill this workshop
        treats as separate from simply knowing the material.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>You keep</strong> packaged takeaways: a CLAUDE.md starter kit, a coordinator-
        subagent reference implementation, a context-degradation diagnostic playbook, an
        architecture-decision-record template, an evaluation harness template, a governance
        checklist, and two personal exam-day prep sheets, one per real exam.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <h2>The runbook</h2>
    <ol>
      <li>
        Prerequisites: comfortable with git, the CLI, and driving Claude Code daily for real
        work; new to the certification's own blueprint specifically, not to Claude itself.
      </li>
      <li>
        Clone it: <code>git clone {REPO}.git</code>
      </li>
      <li>
        Start at <code>modules/README.md</code>. It has the full arc, in order, and a table of
        what each module's gate requires and what you keep from it.
      </li>
      <li>
        Work through Part 1 (Modules 01-06, Architect Foundations), then, if you're continuing,
        Part 2 (Modules 07-10, Architect Professional). Each module states a hard prerequisite
        on an earlier one.
      </li>
      <li>
        No module completes by reading it, and no checkpoint counts if you keep Claude Code
        open while taking it. If a module ever reduces to "read this, then move on," or a link
        here is broken, that's a defect: <a href={`${REPO}/issues`}>open an issue</a>.
      </li>
    </ol>

    <p>
      This workshop is not affiliated with or endorsed by Anthropic, does not guarantee you'll
      pass the real exam, and completing it does not itself credential anything.
    </p>
  </div>

  {
    recentEntries.length > 0 && (
      <>
        <h2 class="mt-14 text-xl font-semibold">Recent from the build log</h2>
        <ul class="mt-6 space-y-4">
          {recentEntries.map((entry) => (
            <li>
              <a href={`${base}build-log/${entry.id}/`} class="entry-card">
                <p class="entry-title text-lg font-semibold">{entry.data.title}</p>
                <p class="mt-1 text-sm opacity-80">{entry.data.description}</p>
              </a>
            </li>
          ))}
        </ul>
        <p class="mt-6 text-sm opacity-70">
          See the <a href={`${base}build-log/`} class="underline">full index</a>.
        </p>
      </>
    )
  }
</BaseLayout>
